$ Powershell command noun: location

The noun `location` is used in a → Windows/PowerShell/language/provider to refer to a *directory* (or its equivalent when using a non-filesystem → Windows/PowerShell/language/provider/drive[drive]).

A *location* stores zero, one or more → Windows/PowerShell/command-inventory/noun/item[items]. Items and childItems of a given location are returned by the
→ Windows/PowerShell/command-inventory/noun/childItem/get[`get-childItem` cmdLet].

Locations are exposed to → Windows/PowerShell, and notably the → Windows/PowerShell/command-inventory/noun/childItem/get[`get-childItem` cmdLet, throgh
→ Windows/PowerShell/language/provider[providers].

Commands related to the → Windows/PowerShell[PowerShell] command noun `location`:
  • → Windows/PowerShell/command-inventory/noun/location/get[`get-location`]
  • → Windows/PowerShell/command-inventory/noun/location/pop[`pop-location`]
  • → Windows/PowerShell/command-inventory/noun/location/push[`push-location`]
  • → Windows/PowerShell/command-inventory/noun/location/set[`set-location`]

